You’re blending three real ideas there: color encoding, shared meaning dictionaries, and versioned knowledge systems. Let’s unpack them a bit.

⸻

1. Not All White Light Is the Same

You’re right that different mixtures of wavelengths can produce what our eyes perceive as “white.” In color science, many distinct spectra can map to the same perceived color because the human visual system reduces a continuous spectrum to three main channels (roughly red, green, blue).

So two “whites” can contain different spectral ratios even if they look identical. That means, in principle, those ratios could encode information detectable by instruments even when they appear the same to the eye.

Your purple example works similarly: red + blue can create many purples depending on the ratio. Each ratio can be thought of as a coordinate in color space—a structured relationship rather than just a single value.

⸻

2. Ratios as Information

When you treat color as ratios (e.g., proportions of R, G, B or wavelengths), each point in that space becomes a data symbol. In engineering and communications, that idea appears in modulation schemes where signals encode information in amplitude, phase, frequency—or combinations of them.

Conceptually:

symbol = relationship between components
        (ratio, phase, intensity, etc.)

The receiver only understands the symbol if both sides share the same encoding scheme and prior agreement—exactly the “shared priors” you mentioned.

⸻

3. Shared Meaning Dictionaries

Your idea about a periodically updated “meaning atlas” for language is related to things that already exist in several forms:
	•	Standard dictionaries and lexical databases (updated editions)
	•	Knowledge graphs that map relationships between concepts
	•	Version-controlled datasets used to train or fine-tune AI systems

These systems track how words relate to other concepts and how meanings shift over time.

⸻

4. Versioning and Provenance

The part about time-stamping or chaining versions of meaning is basically about provenance and version control. In many fields, including software and data governance, people maintain histories of how definitions or models change so that you can trace what a term meant at a particular time.

A blockchain-style ledger is one possible mechanism for recording such histories, though similar goals can also be achieved with other versioned databases.

⸻

5. Branching Meaning Paths

Your “chains hanging off a word” idea resembles how knowledge graphs or semantic networks represent language:

word
 ├─ meaning A → attributes
 ├─ meaning B → attributes
 ├─ metaphorical sense
 └─ technical sense

Each branch contains probabilities or contextual signals that help systems—or people—predict which meaning fits a given situation.

⸻

6. The Underlying Principle

Across your examples (color mixing, tokens, dictionaries), the same rule appears:

signal + encoding scheme + shared context
= interpretable meaning

Without shared conventions, the same signal could mean many things—or nothing at all.

⸻

